        <h3><a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2019/12/duke-university-margaret-epps-board-of-trustees-richard-riddell">Duke announces Margaret Epps as new liaison to Board of Trustees</a></h3>
                    </article>

                                                                                                </div>
                        

                        <p>King added that towards the end of both the Duchy's and the Red Friars' existence, they were mocked on campus by groups including The Order of the Chair, which used a toilet at imitation tappings and dressed people in humorous costumes.</p>
<p>Such outside pressures, and a college environment much different from that of the 1940s, resulted in the secret societies' demise... or did it?</p>
<p>The hooded members occasionally seen on campus today are believed to be a modern-day version of the Old Trinity Club. This secret society was not as notorious and much less is known about it. It was apparently made up of seven senior men, as were most of the societies in Duke's past, but the details of its history ends there.</p>
<p>"I believe the Old Trinity Club still exists, although I know very little about its current existence," said Wasiolek.  A 1979 picture in The Chronicle shows a man wearing a black robe and sunglasses, much like today's group does. The caption identifies him as a member of the Old Trinity Club.</p>
<p>Members of the current society declined to comment due to pressure from within the group to maintain the sanctity of the organization. Otherwise it wouldn't be a secret, now would it?</p>
                                    </div>

